Glenn - thanks for confirming this for me. I called back to the
dealership and spoke with the service manager after posting this
question and got the same story about the failure needing to be linked
to an emissions test failure to be covered and was referred to section
5.2 of the warranty manual for justification of this claim. I tried to
explain to him that's not how the federal regulation or the warranty
manual reads and asked for the general manager of the dealership and was
told he was unavailable. The service manager then quipped that even if
it were covered I was still responsible for a sizeable bill for the
diagnostic work to track the problem to the PCM. Interestingly enough, I
already had a diagnostic test run by a local service center before going
to the dealer and they were able to tell me within an hour that the PCM
was the problem, but they were unable to fix the problem so I had it
towed to the dealership (I didn't inquire as to why I just took the guy
at his word that he couldn't do the repair). I told the dealership when
I dropped off the van what the previous service center has said, but
they still ran their own diagnostic tests anyway. I guess my next call
will be to Chrysler's customer service department

